{"/service/ndnp/msar/batch_msar_gabardine_ver01/data/sn87065163/00199916804/1908031301/0056.xml":{"full_text":"A\nKVi 1 Daily News\nK.\nm.\nX\n_\nVOL I. NO 265\nHATTIESBURG. MISSISSIPPI. FRIDAY MORNING. MARCH 13. 1908\nPRICE FIVE Cl\nMISSISSIPPI PINE ASSOCIATION'S\no\nR. L BENNETT DELIVERS\nAN. INTERESTING ADDRESS\n^Enormous Shipments of Lumber\nOver Gulf Ship Island Rail\nroad to Gulfport.\ni J. F. Wilder la Again Chosen Presi\ndent and Ewing A. Walker It Re\ntained a* Secretary\u2014Concatenation\nof Hoo-Hoo.\nThe Mississippi Pine Association\nmet In the private dining room of Hotel\n.Hattiesburg at 10:30 a. m. yesterday\nmorning (12th). This was the occa\nsion of the annual meeting of that\nassociation, composed of manufactur\nl ers and wholesalers of yellow pine.\nThq meeting was called to order by\nMr. J. F. Wilder, of Epps, who Is the\nefficient president of the organization.\nMr. Wilder read, his annual address,\nreviewing the work of the association\nand treating of subjects of importance\nto those connected therewith. He\nurged the great need of co-operation\nand the necessity for an active, earn\nest support of the association by the\nmen engaged in the yellow pine busi\nness. Showing from statistics that\nparticular lumber section represents\nupwards of one-third the lumber out\nput of the United States. A matter\nof great significance to this section\nwas his statement that the Gulf and\nShip Island Railroad handled in 190J.\nupwards of 3,600 cars bf lumber for\nthe interior, while a quarter of a bil\nlion feet of lumber passed over the\nsame road to Gulfport for export ship\nment. That upwards of 800 mtllion\nfeet of lumber were handled out of\nthis section In one year over one rail\nroad signifies much for our section and\nthis he emphasized.\nThere f were several interesting\nspeeches and suggestions from differ\nent members of the association.\nThe following splendid paper was\n$ead by Mr. R. L. Bennett, of the\nHattiesburg Banking and Trust Com\npany.\nAddress of R. L. Bennett before the\nmeeting of the Mississippi Pine As\nsociation, Hattiesburg, March 12, 1908.\nMan Is ever learning, but never com\ning to a knowledge of the truth. This\nis a fact only iff-a qualified sense. We\ndo learn, but some times forget our\nlessons. Experience is a hard school\nmaster, but many of us Insist on at\ntending his classes. Life presents\nnot only opportunity, but evolves is\nsues that are useful if not eternal. In\nour social Intercourse, man touch their\nfellows and influence them for good\n\u25a0or ill. This thought suggests, 'then, the\npossibilities that lie before us In our\ndesire to fill our place In the body\npolitic. No one man knows all things\n\u2014therefore every man has laid on him\nthe duty of sharing his thought\"and\ninfluendl with his fellows. Men jflth\ncommon interest find It nol only In\nstructive but profitable to meet to\ngether In council for the discussion of\nquestions with which they are familiar.\nThe interchange of Ideas is useful, and\nhe who Is keenest to note the opinions\nof his fellows is most likely to Require\nopinions of his own. An assembly of\nmen engaged in the development of\nany great Industry, or the handling\nof any staple product, makes possible\nconsideration of the conditions which\neffect their vocation and determine its\nresults. Our section is known as the\nyellow pine belt, because yellow pine\nforests have been and are our chief\nsource of wealth; therefore, anything\nthat we can learn relative to these Is,\n(Continued on'page three.)\nSIX CHINAMEN\nBURNED TO DEATH\nAssociated Press.\nj>' Maryville, Cal., March 12\u2014 Six Chi\nnese are dead and two others badly\nihjured as a result of what is believed\nto have been an incendiary fire here\ntoday.\n\u2022;JS\n\nMAN WHO SHOT PRIEST\nSENTENCED TO HANG.\n\n\n\n\nAssociated Press.\nDenver, March 12.\u2014Guisseppe\nAlla, who shot and killed father\nLeo Heinrichs at St. Elizabeth's\nChurch, In this city, on Fobru-\nary 23, was today found guilty\nof murder In the first degree and.\nhanging was fixed, as the penalty\nby the jury. The date\necutlon has not as\nnamed.\n\n\n\n,1?\ne'ex-\nbeen\n\nOCEAN RECORD\nAGAIN SMASHED\nAssociated Press.\nQueenstown, March 12.\u2014The ocean\nsteamer Mauretania has established\na new trans-Atlantic record by beating\nher own best previous eastward rec\nord by two hours and thirty-six min\nutes.\nHer time from Sandy Hook lightship\nto Daunt's Rock was five days and five\nminutes. She traveled over a longer\nroute than before, traversing 2,932\nknots.\nJohn Mitchell May Prevent\nImpending Strife in Coal\nRegions of Central States\ni\n:t\n\nm\n\nAS\ni\n7\ns\ni:\n\u25a0\u2022v\n\nI\n7\n\nI\nt\ni\n7'7\n\u25a0{K^l\nm\n\nm\n\n\nilfl\n\u2022VA,\n\n\n7\n7*\n1\nW ;7\nm\n7\n'7 c\ny\n7'7:\nm\nHi,\n\nm\n77\nm\n\nis\nIP\n\n\u2022\u2022V.V\n8\n\ni a\n\ni\n\"tt\n.V V;\nm\n\n1\ng\u00a7\n7\npi\n77-7\n\ni\nI\ni\nVi\nj\n\n\u2022Mi\nm.\nN\n1\n7\n1\ny'j\nW0i\n\"A,.\nI\nEre!\ni\nME\nSi\nIf\n\na\nIP\n77\nfeii\nIndianapolis, March 12.\u2014Has John\nMitchell, retiring president of t the\nUnited Mine Workers, more influence\nthan Tom L. Lewis, president-elect,\nwho is to take office the first of next\nmonth? On the answer Is believed to\ndepend the question of whether there\nwill be a general suspension of bitum\ninous coal mining in Western Penn\nsylvania, Ohio, Indiana and Illinois.\nThe question of the Influence of the\ntwo leaders is to be fought out in the\nconvention which began today, and\nadherents of both are prepared for a\nUv ely contest. If Mitchell carries the\nconvention the operators In Indians\nHAS\nMADE GAINS\nTwo Congressional Districts in Mis\nsouri Have Endorsed the\nNew York Candidate\nROOSEVELT IS ENDORSED\nIN THE STATE PLATFORM\nBoth Districts Endorse the Adminis\ntration of Roosevelt\u2014Delegates of\nEleventh District Are to Go Unin\nstructed.\nAssociated Press.\nSt. Louis, March 12.\u2014The Repub\nlican conventions held today in the\nEleventh and Twelfth Missouri dis\ntricts to elect delegates to the nation\nal convention adopted resolutions en\nand Illinois will be allowed to settle\nwith their miners as separate states\nor Jointly, as they-may elect. If l^ewis\nwins the suspension will be general.\n-The operators in Ohio are said to\nfator a strike.\nThey have millions\nof ,tons of coal on hand, and, should\na strike take place, they believe they\ncandlspose of a large part of it In\nIndiana and Illinois markets.\nThe operators in Illinois and Indiana\nhave practically come to an under\nstanding, and they do not want a gen\neral suspension. They feel that the\nsituation hinges entirely on whether\nPresident Mitchell can carry his policy\nthrough the convention.\ni\nPRINCE OF LIARS PLEADS GUILTY, BUT\nFEARS DEATH AT HANDS OF ASSASSIN\n/iC^MiiiiuwiiimmiMimiminmi\nv t f\ny\nV.\nmm\n;V :f i\nI:'-?\nT\n\nWM\n\n.I\nf7\\\n7\ni\nfw\n>V\n\n4|S.:\nI\nmu\nHARRY ORCHARD AND HIS GUARDS.\ndorsing Governor Charles E. Hughes,\nof New York, for the presidency, and\nthe delegates from the Twelfth dis\ntrict are instructed for him. The\nEleventh district delegates are unin\nstructed.\nThe instructions given the Twelfth\ndistrict delegates are the first instruc\ntions for Hughes given by any con\ngressional district convention thus\nfar held in the country.\nResolutions were adopted endorsing\nthe administration\nRoosevelt.\nicf President\nDelegates to Chicago Will Vote For\nTaft \"First, Last and\nAll the Time.\n\nFIRST INSTRUCTIONS YET\nMADE OUTSIDE NEW YORK\nWhich Is Similar to That of Ohio,\nQuoting That Document Literally\nin Reference to the Tariff\nIssue.\nAssociated Press.\nOmaha, Neb., March 12.\u2014Without\na voice of dissent, the candidacy of\nWilliam H. Taft for President was en\ndorsed by the Republican state con\nvention* Here tdfiay. A\ntion for Taft will go to Chicago in\nstructed to vote for his nomination\n\"first, last and all the time.\"\nCharles B. Anderson was made per\nmanent chairman of the convention.\nThe platform is given over princi\npally to the endorsement of Roosevelt's\nadministration. It follows closely the\nlines laid down in the Ohio platform\nand quotes that document literally In\ndefining the tariff issue.\nk solid- delega\nBLACK HAND IN\nRANKIN COUNTY\n\u2022Associated Press.\nBrandon, Miss., March 12.\u2014The citi\nof Plain, a small town in this\nzens\ncounty, the very much excited over\nBlack Hand letters re\nnumerous\nceived by citizens of the community\nduring the past several days. A mass\nmeeting has been held and an effort\nwill be made to apprehend the guilty\nparties. All of the letters demand\nmoney and threaten the lives of those\nwho refuse to comply.\n\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666('\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666\u2666'I'\nTHE WEATHER.\n\n\n\nWashington. March 12.\u2014Fair\nFriday and Saturday; warmer\nFriday in east portion, light south\nwest winds.\n\n\nHARRY ORCHARD\nPLEADS GUILTY\nAssociated Press.\nCaldwell, Ir., March 12.\u2014Harry Or\nchard today, before Judge Fremont\nWood in the district court, was al\n\n\nn, x\ni\ns|gg\nUp\n\n\n^S5S5\nn\n17AKRY OUCUAKD.\nlowed to withdraw nit>- iu. mer- pies of I\nnot guilty, entered at his first arraign\nmen by order of the court when he\nstood mute, and enter another plea of\nguilty to. the charge of murdering for\nmer Governor SJeunanberg by the ex\nplosion of a dynamite bomb at the\nside gate of his residence here early\nin the evening of December 30, 1906\nHe will be sentenced March 18.\n\nLOUISIANA DEMOCRATS\nTO CHOOSE DELEGATES\nAssociated Press.\nNew Orleans, March 12.\u2014The Dem\nocratic state executive committee to\nnight fixed June 3 as the date for\nholding the state convention to elect\ndelegates to Denver. The state con-1\nvention will be held in Baton Rouge. I\nm\n7\n-pw\nf*y\n\u25a0a\nVv'\nv\n\nTOM U JOHNSON.\nMayor of Cleveland, who denounces\nbuilding inspector of Collinwood as\nman responsible for death of 176 child\nren in recent fire.\nCORTELMI\nSupreme Court of District of Colum\nbia Sustains His Action\nDuring Crisis\nISMISSED\nNew Yorker Will\nUnited States Supreme CouT^VQ|\nteresting Aftermath of the Recent\nFinancial Panic.\nWashington, March'12.\u2014The su\npreme court of the District of Colum\nbia has dismissed the proceedings\nInstituted some months ago by George\nW. Austin, of New York, to compel j\nthe secretary of the treasury to Issue j\nhim $3,000,000 vqortth of Panama canal\nbonds.\nThe court holds that the secretary\nhad the righ\u201e to reject any ana all bids\nand to consider the financial condition\nof the country, and that if the courts\nwere to enjoin such proceedings a syn\ndicate might get control of the entire\nbond issue and cause a financial panic.\nAustin has appealed his case to the\nUnited States supreme court.\nCOTTON MILLS\nARE HARD HIT\nPoor Demand For Goods and High\nPrice of Cotton Cause\nWage Redaction\nj\n\nLOWELL MANUFACTURES\nANNOUNCE SUBSTANTIAL CUT\nI\nOtheVs to Follow Latter Part of A\nand Many Thousand Employes Will\nBe Seriously Effected by the\nCurtailment.\nAssociated Press\nBoston, Starch 12.\u2014A general re\nduction in the production of cotton\nmill operators in the north will be\nmade thp latter part of April, npoord\ning to an agreement reached by the\nmill men today. Notices have been\nposted in all of the cotton mills of\nLow-ell and other cities in this state\nthat the wages of 20,000 operatives\nwill be reduced 10 per cent, on March\nI\nj\nEngland will post notices during the j\nnext few days announcing a reduction. I\nThe manufacturers give as a rea- j\non for the change In wages the depres\nslon in the cloth market and the high\nprice of cotton.\n13.\nIt is understood that practically all\nof the cotton mills in northern New\nThe cottn mills in New England\nemploy about 166,000 persons.\nARKANSAS REPUBLICANS.\nAssociataed Press.\nLittle Rock, Ark., March 12.\u2014It Is\nannounced that the Republican state\ncommittee will meet a week from to\nmorrow to select a date for the state\nconvention. Friends of Taft will at\ntempt to secure his indorsement by the\ncommittee.\nAmerican Battleship Fleet\nNears End of Long Journeyi\nSan Diego, Cal., March 12.\u2014The\nAmerican battleship fleet, under com\nmand of Rear Admiral Robley D.\nEvans, anchored In Magdelena Bay\ntoday, practically ending the 13,000\nmile cruise began at Hampton Roads\nless than three months ago.\nLODGE TAl\nTO\n\nMassachusetts Senator Mai\nFor Enactment of the A\nCurrency Measure\nRAILROAD MAIL SERVICE\nDISCUSSED IN THI\nWei\nvise\nDepartment.\nt\nAssociated Press.\nMarch 12.\u2014Senator\nWashington,\nLodge, of Massachusetts, today strong\nly endorsed tne pending currency bill\nj in the senate, declaring it to be servlce\nj a ble as an emergency measure, and\nthat it would not prevent the enact\nment of a general currency law, which\nhe declared he hoped to see realized\nin the future on the basis of a great\ncentral bank,\nposed the currency bill, especially\ncondemning the proposition to Insure\nbank deposits,\nSenator Paynter, of Kentucky, op\nThe postoffice appropriation bill was\nhalted at every turn in the house today\nby amenidments upon which there was\nlengthy discussion. _\nThe house was a unit for withholding\na portion of the pay to railroads for\ncarrying United States malls until a\ncorrect system of weighing cffuld be\nestablish\nbeing ina\nA vigol\na provision to that effect f\n^M^din the measure, Vwj\n(position of Senator\nmade on\nGoebel, of Ohio, tq Jjjyregse by $2,\n000,000 the appropriation for defray\ning the expenses of railway\nclerks while traveling on business of\nmail\nthe department.\nj Still other amendments *ere\nsight when the hous\u00a3 adjourned.\nDEATH CHEATS\nNEW YORK COURT\nAssociated. Press\nNew York, March 12.\u2014John G. Jen\nkins. a Brooklyn banker who with h' A\nthree sons, was Indicted as a res 1\nof the banking Investigation whi -J\n^followed the recent financial pani. iy\ndied at Sea Cliff, L. I., today, death!\nbeing due to paralysis.\nPACIFIC UOAST\nHEAVY FOR BRYAN\nAssociated Press.\nFresno. Cal,. March 12.\u2014Great In-'*'\nfluence is being brought to bear by Cal-\nifornia Democrats to secure the pres- i\nj ence of William J. Bryan at the state J\nj convention to be held here on May l\nI is.\nj thasiastic convention. Inaugurating a\nrousing Democratic campaign In the\nGolden State,\n__\nPlans have been made for an en\nTO GALLOWS ON FRIDAY 1\nTTHE THIRTEENTH I\nNorfolk, Va., March 12.\u2014If Governor\nSwanson does not interfere, Leo C.\nThurman, convicted of murder in the\nfirst degree, will be hanged tomor.ow.S-i\nA petition to the governor, as'Mug that\nhe refrain from interv -.lng in Thur\nman s hqLilf, La\u00bb oeen circulated by\nDr. H. E. Johnson, of Suffolk, one of\nthe best known Methodist clergymen.\nof the Virginia conference.\nThe trip ffom Magdelena Bay to|\nSan Francisco, the destination orlgin-J\nally announced, is a distance of about!\n1,000 miles, but this will not be trav-J\nersed until after target practice iJ\ncompleted apd the fleet drills are coni\neluded.","height":"17208","width":"13992"}}
